x \equiv -1 \pmod{4}
x \equiv -1 \pmod{5}
x \equiv -1 \pmod{6}
\] This implies that \( x + 1 \) is a common multiple of 4, 5, and 6. The smallest positive \( x \) is when \( x + 1 \) is the least common multiple (LCM) of 4, 5, and 6. The LCM of 4, 5, and 6 is 60. Therefore, \( x + 1 = 60 \), so \( x = 59 \). The smallest possible positive integer value of \( x \) is 59. </think> <answer> 59</answer>

